column10:
Status 
"In Prep" -  preparing buoy for deployment
"Active" - at sea and we plan to recover
"Lost" - at sea but unlikely we can recover
“Sunk” - only recovered partial buoy, assumed dead, sunk, and highly unlikely to recover
“Complete” -  buoy recovered and data is in house "Unusable" - buoy recovered but data is unusable

column68: CCC Pilot Project. We threw the small buoy with the little yellow float and attached the array to a small (10 lb?) blue dumbell anchor but it wasn't heavy enough to sink the subsurface float so the entire array was floaing on the surface. Recordings are probably not great

column68: Had extra time in the afternoon and decided to tow the array between 8-10kts, stayed further offshore because of the length of the tow cable. A lot of gray whales were seen previous days. No animals were seen and the array was pulled in

Location 1 on map from Jeff. Head piece flooded and terminals between the spots and the batteries are fried. Wav files have knocking below 3kHz from trailing buoy hitting the PIFSC buoy

Location C on map from Jeff. Karin and the leg 3 team pulled it on board without the subsurface buoy, array or anchor. The line looked pretty frayed. Maybe a shark bit it or it got tangled around the dampener plate and chaffed itself apart?
Location 5 on map from Jeff. Recorder stopped recording after the first SD card? I will bench test it and see if I can figure out what happened

Deployed in Eureka WEA, Testing modified PIFSC buoy (10lbs drilled to the spar)

Deployed in Eureka WEA, Testing modified PIFSC buoy (10lbs drilled to the spar). Spot AD was not always reporting it's location consistently but then later in the day all of the locations would show up at once on the website. Recovered without leaking in head piece, must be a Spot interface issue
